            <div id="id3" style="height: 2266px; left: 20px; position: absolute; top: 290px; width: 978px; z-index: 1; " class="style_SkipStroke_3 shape-with-text">
              <div class="text-content style_External_978_2266" style="padding: 0px; ">
                <div class="style_2">
                  <p style="padding-top: 0pt; " class="paragraph_style"><br /></p>
                  <p class="paragraph_style">Let’s consider an asset with stock price S(t), where t denotes time. As usual the equation is <br /></p>
                  <div class="paragraph paragraph_style"><div style="height: 17px; width: 161px;  height: 17px; position: relative; width: 161px; " class="tinyText style_SkipStroke_2 inline-block"><img src="Numeraire_files/droppedImage.jpg" alt="" style="border: none; height: 17px; width: 161px; " /></div><br /></div>
                  <p class="paragraph_style"><br /></p>
                  <p class="paragraph_style">Note: At this point I have no idea what the drift term is, so it’s NOT the black scholes drift = r. <br /></p>
                  <p class="paragraph_style"><br /></p>
                  <p class="paragraph_style">For simplicity I will assume all dividends are reinvested and so I use another variable<br /></p>
                  <p class="paragraph_style"><br /></p>
                  <div class="paragraph paragraph_style"><div style="height: 20px; width: 104px;  height: 20px; position: relative; width: 104px; " class="tinyText style_SkipStroke_2 inline-block"><img src="Numeraire_files/droppedImage_1.jpg" alt="" style="border: none; height: 20px; width: 104px; " /></div> .....(1)<br /></div>
                  <p class="paragraph_style"><br /></p>
                  <p class="paragraph_style">Applying Ito’s lemma to V(t), I will get<br /></p>
                  <p class="paragraph_style"><br /></p>
                  <div class="paragraph paragraph_style"><div style="height: 22px; width: 104px;  height: 22px; position: relative; width: 104px; " class="tinyText style_SkipStroke_2 inline-block"><img src="Numeraire_files/droppedImage_2.jpg" alt="" style="border: none; height: 22px; width: 104px; " /></div><br /></div>
                  <p class="paragraph_style"><br /></p>
                  <div class="paragraph paragraph_style"><div style="height: 28px; width: 119px;  height: 28px; position: relative; width: 119px; " class="tinyText style_SkipStroke_2 inline-block"><img src="Numeraire_files/droppedImage_3.jpg" alt="" style="border: none; height: 28px; width: 119px; " /></div><br /></div>
                  <p class="paragraph_style"><br /></p>
                  <p class="paragraph_style">Now as per black scholes V(t) / R(t) is a martingale. Here R(t) is acting as a Numeraire or in more precise terms if I measure the value V(t) at each time step and divide by R(t) the drift is constant and only movement that will be observed will be due to the random or stochastic term  <br /></p>
                  <p class="paragraph_style"><br /></p>
                  <p class="paragraph_style_1">Risk Neutral Rate as Numeraire<br /></p>
                  <p class="paragraph_style"><br /></p>
                  <p class="paragraph_style">Any equation which has both drift and stochastic term is difficult to solve. So all I am doing is trying to get rid of drift term.<br /></p>
                  <p class="paragraph_style">Let’s take another variable<br /></p>
                  <p class="paragraph_style"><br /></p>
                  <div class="paragraph paragraph_style"><div style="height: 27px; width: 83px;  height: 27px; position: relative; width: 83px; " class="tinyText style_SkipStroke_2 inline-block"><img src="Numeraire_files/droppedImage_4.jpg" alt="" style="border: none; height: 27px; width: 83px; " /></div><br /></div>
                  <p class="paragraph_style"><br /></p>
                  <p class="paragraph_style">Applying Ito’s lemma to Z(t) we will get,<br /></p>
                  <p class="paragraph_style"><br /></p>
                  <p class="paragraph_style">Note: Sometimes I remove the index (t) for simplicity or laziness, but as usual it’s always there.<br /></p>
                  <p class="paragraph_style"><br /></p>
                  <div class="paragraph paragraph_style"><div style="height: 22px; width: 119px;  height: 22px; position: relative; width: 119px; " class="tinyText style_SkipStroke_2 inline-block"><img src="Numeraire_files/droppedImage_5.jpg" alt="" style="border: none; height: 22px; width: 119px; " /></div><br /></div>
                  <p class="paragraph_style"><br /></p>
                  <p class="paragraph_style">Using equation ……(1) I can write above as<br /></p>
                  <p class="paragraph_style"><br /></p>
                  <div class="paragraph paragraph_style"><div style="height: 22px; width: 144px;  height: 22px; position: relative; width: 144px; " class="tinyText style_SkipStroke_2 inline-block"><img src="Numeraire_files/droppedImage_6.jpg" alt="" style="border: none; height: 22px; width: 144px; " /></div><br /></div>
                  <p class="paragraph_style"><br /></p>
                  <p class="paragraph_style"><br /></p>
                  <p class="paragraph_style">Since Z(t) is a martingale to make the drift term zero we should have<br /></p>
                  <p class="paragraph_style"><br /></p>
                  <div class="paragraph paragraph_style"><div style="height: 22px; width: 169px;  height: 22px; position: relative; width: 169px; " class="tinyText style_SkipStroke_2 inline-block"><img src="Numeraire_files/droppedImage_7.jpg" alt="" style="border: none; height: 22px; width: 169px; " /></div><br /></div>
                  <p class="paragraph_style"><br /></p>
                  <p class="paragraph_style">And that is why we use drift = (r-q) dt in Black Scholes. That was easy, but this concept is extremely powerful in pricing seemingly complicated structures like Quanto’s, Margrabe (Exchange Option) or basically derivation of formulas. Generally asked in Quant interviews to check basic concepts.<br /></p>
                  <p class="paragraph_style"><br /></p>
                  <div class="paragraph paragraph_style">Now let’s take up , and here instead of R(t), we are using V(t) as Numeraire or underlying as Numeraire.  <div style="height: 27px; width: 83px;  height: 27px; position: relative; width: 83px; " class="tinyText style_SkipStroke_2 inline-block"><img src="Numeraire_files/droppedImage_8.jpg" alt="" style="border: none; height: 27px; width: 83px; " /></div><br /></div>
                  <p class="paragraph_style"><br /></p>
                  <div class="paragraph paragraph_style">Applying Ito’s lemma I get  <div style="height: 26px; width: 173px;  height: 26px; position: relative; width: 173px; " class="tinyText style_SkipStroke_2 inline-block"><img src="Numeraire_files/droppedImage_9.jpg" alt="" style="border: none; height: 26px; width: 173px; " /></div><br /></div>
                  <p class="paragraph_style"><br /></p>
                  <p class="paragraph_style">Substituting the values of dV to make this equation in dS we have<br /></p>
                  <p class="paragraph_style"><br /></p>
                  <div class="paragraph paragraph_style"><div style="height: 22px; width: 182px;  height: 22px; position: relative; width: 182px; " class="tinyText style_SkipStroke_2 inline-block"><img src="Numeraire_files/droppedImage_10.jpg" alt="" style="border: none; height: 22px; width: 182px; " /></div> ...........(2)<br /></div>
                  <p class="paragraph_style"> <br /></p>
                  <div class="paragraph paragraph_style">So when I use underlying asset as Numeraire I should have drift for dS as <div style="height: 20px; width: 85px;  height: 20px; position: relative; width: 85px; " class="tinyText style_SkipStroke_2 inline-block"><img src="Numeraire_files/droppedImage_11.jpg" alt="" style="border: none; height: 20px; width: 85px; " /></div><br /></div>
                  <p class="paragraph_style"><br /></p>
                  <p class="paragraph_style">, which is what we normally use in Black-Scholes. Usual argument is to make Z(t) a martingale.<br /></p>
                  <p class="paragraph_style"><br /></p>
                  <p class="paragraph_style_2"><span class="style_3"> </span>Another Asset as Numeraire<br /></p>
                  <p class="paragraph_style_2"><br /></p>
                  <div class="paragraph paragraph_style">If I move more towards generalization and include another risky asset A(t) as Numeraire, or mathematically  <div style="height: 27px; width: 83px;  height: 27px; position: relative; width: 83px; " class="tinyText style_SkipStroke_2 inline-block"><img src="Numeraire_files/droppedImage_12.jpg" alt="" style="border: none; height: 27px; width: 83px; " /></div><br /></div>
                  <div class="paragraph paragraph_style">Also assuming the Instantaneous correlation is where dB indicates Brownian motion.  <div style="height: 19px; width: 143px;  height: 19px; position: relative; width: 143px; " class="tinyText style_SkipStroke_2 inline-block"><img src="Numeraire_files/droppedImage_13.jpg" alt="" style="border: none; height: 19px; width: 143px; " /></div><br /></div>
                  <p class="paragraph_style"><br /></p>
                  <div class="paragraph paragraph_style">Applying Ito’s lemma we again have <div style="height: 22px; width: 255px;  height: 22px; position: relative; width: 255px; " class="tinyText style_SkipStroke_2 inline-block"><img src="Numeraire_files/droppedImage_14.jpg" alt="" style="border: none; height: 22px; width: 255px; " /></div><br /></div>
                  <p class="paragraph_style"><br /></p>
                  <div class="paragraph paragraph_style">And using dS instead of dV, <div style="height: 22px; width: 267px;  height: 22px; position: relative; width: 267px; " class="tinyText style_SkipStroke_2 inline-block"><img src="Numeraire_files/droppedImage_15.jpg" alt="" style="border: none; height: 22px; width: 267px; " /></div><br /></div>
                  <p class="paragraph_style"><br /></p>
                  <p class="paragraph_style"><br /></p>
                  <p class="paragraph_style"><br /></p>
                  <p class="paragraph_style_2"><span class="style_3"> </span>Appendix<br /></p>
                  <p class="paragraph_style_2"><br /></p>
                  <p class="paragraph_style">What I know most of people will hate is bookish language “Applying Ito’s lemma without any explanation, so here it is”<br /></p>
                  <p class="paragraph_style"><br /></p>
                  <p class="paragraph_style">If Z = P(t,X,Y) then<br /></p>
                  <p class="paragraph_style"><br /></p>
                  <p class="paragraph_style">As per Ito’s lemma <br /></p>
                  <p class="paragraph_style"><br /></p>
                  <div class="paragraph paragraph_style"><div style="height: 25px; width: 539px;  height: 25px; position: relative; width: 539px; " class="tinyText style_SkipStroke_2 inline-block"><img src="Numeraire_files/droppedImage_16.jpg" alt="" style="border: none; height: 25px; width: 539px; " /></div><br /></div>
                  <p class="paragraph_style">Now use let’s say Z = V(t) / R(t) and apply above equation. Same for other equations……<br /></p>
                  <p class="paragraph_style"><br /></p>
                  <p class="paragraph_style"><br /></p>
                  <p class="paragraph_style"><br /></p>
                  <p class="paragraph_style"><br /></p>
                  <p class="paragraph_style"><br /></p>
                </div>
